context.text: The 100 Most Topographically Isolated Major Mountain Peaks of Canada
Mountain peaks of Canada - Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
Rank Peak Province Range Elevation Prominence Isolation

The following sortable table lists the 100 most topographically isolated major mountain peaks of Canada with a topographic prominence of at least 500 m (1,640 ft). Topographic isolation is the minimum great circle distance to a point of higher elevation. A total of 62 of these most isolated peaks are located in British Columbia, 15 in Nunavut, 11 in the Yukon, 7 in Newfoundland and Labrador, 5 in Alberta, 2 in Quebec, and 1 each in the Northwest Territories and New Brunswick.

The following sortable table lists the 100 most topographically prominent major mountain peaks of Canada. Topographic prominence is defined as the elevation difference between the summit and the highest or key col to a higher summit. A total of 72 of these most prominent peaks are located in British Columbia, 15 in the Yukon, 10 in Nunavut, 6 in Alberta, and 1 in the Northwest Territories.
Mount Logan in the Yukon is the highest peak of Canada

The following sortable table lists the 100 highest major mountain peaks of Canada. Each of the following peaks has a topographic prominence of at least 500 m (1,640 ft). Topographic elevation is defined as the vertical distance above the reference geoid , a precise mathematical model of the Earth's sea level as an equipotential gravitational surface . A total of 69 of these highest peaks are located in British Columbia, 25 in the Yukon, 10 in Alberta, and 1 each in the Northwest Territories and Nunavut.
Mount Saint Elias on the boundary between the Yukon and Alaska is the second highest peak of both Canada and the United States

This article comprises three sortable tables of major mountain peaks of Canada . This article defines a major mountain peak as a summit with a topographic prominence of at least 500 m (1,640 ft ). Topographic prominence is defined as the elevation difference between the summit and the highest or key col to a higher summit.
Main articles: Geography of Canada and Mountain peaks of North America
Mount Fairweather on the boundary between British Columbia and Alaska is the second most topographically prominent peak of Canada
Mount Logan in the Yukon is the highest peak of Canada.
